The ČSSD in Prague doesn't know Voldemort or the bakery.
The new ČSSD councillors in the capital will apparently have to overcome the obvious language barriers so that the members of the Prague Board and the City Council understand their renewed SDG colleagues.
The Aktualně.cz period "examined" the members of the new ČSSD Council to check their knowledge of the slang language that has emerged in recent years in the Council, when the current members of the coalition ruled Prague.
The coded dictionary that used Prague's political flower and cream during the previous period, by Mayor Pavel Bém, includes some of the best-known characters, situations and causes of the metropolis.
Surprisingly, it has been found that the new councillors hardly understand these well-known concepts.
At least that's what they say.
"Who's Voldemort?"
"I really don't know."
"I'm more of a novice in Prague politics," said Culture Councilman Lukáš Kaucký during the "colleague" terminology examination.
And as far as the veteran politician is concerned, Karel Březina reacted the same.
Maybe they know the concept of today's golf.
"Possibly it's the only expression of all of you who asked me what I use from time to time."
"If not, I usually don't use slang."
From the glossary, whose definitions were published in the Aktualně.cz newspaper last June before the SDG voting congress, the editorial board chose six examples, in particular those that are particularly related to the municipal authorities of Prague.
The socialists had to explain the concepts "Voldemort", "the biggest golf hole in Prague", "go to the pastry shop", "the bull's neck", "treason from the capital" and "blindar".
Three councillors agreed to take the test and a quarter, Antonín Weinert, who in future will be responsible for education in Prague, initially agreed, but did not pick up the phone again.
The fifth councillor, Petr Dolinek, refused directly to do so.
"I don't get involved in these things and I don't want to appreciate how civic Democrats have fun."
"What I do care about is how we will understand each other in the execution of our programs," he said.
As has been seen, Councilman Lukáš Kaucký allegedly would not have realized that the previous title is an expression about an influential businessman and a friend of former Mayor Bém, Roman Janoušek.
To Kaucký the word "Voldemort" does not say anything; the only term that was right in the exam is "the largest golf hole in Prague".
"It's the Blanka tunnel," Kaucký says, adding immediately, "But I know it from the news."
"I'm going to have to sign up for a language course," he jokes.
Karel Březina is not the only one who recognizes the Blanka tunnel in the golf hole, but also the Environment Councillor Lukáš Plachý.
Afterward, both socio-democrats know who Voldemort and Lukáš Plachý really is and even knows where to find that character; he also suspects the meaning of "going to the pastry shop".
"I think it means going to a company in Prague"; soon it is revealed to Plachý that it is the headquarters of the companies of Janoušek.
Like Březina, he indicates that such knowledge gained them from the news, but that he does not use such vocabulary.
According to the test participants, among the socio-democrats there is no such familiar glossary of colloquial terms.
"I asked my colleagues, but we really don't seem to have anything like it."
"Rather, among us we use nicknames, sometimes abbreviations, or we play word games with names," says the president of the ČSSD Prague, Petr Hulinský, whose party partners call Hulda.
"At school they called me Bříza, but I don't know if my classmates also call me that," confesses his own nickname Karel Březina.
The Aktualně.cz newspaper tested the name and it works.
For his party partners, Weinert is Děda (similar to "yayo") or, less friendly, Dědek ("old"), the representative Miroslav Poche, with whom they associated before the election deceptions during the party sponsorship, receives the nickname "Igráček" ("playmobil") from some of his companions.
Nicknames are also the only expressions that socio-democrats tolerate in speech within the party.
Hulinský does not like to be called Hulda, but the Aktualně.cz newspaper discovered even other nicknames for this Prague president.
"The doctor of baton rights" apparently recalls that Petr Hulinský obtained his doctorate in law at the Bratislava police academy.
The Government wants to limit the torture of “witches”, as it published in a brochure
Women considered witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They tend to be older, unable to work, for example, for health reasons, they are single and have no children.
Women who "turn" witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the village.
"Men rarely suffer such but."
"Neither is healthy young women isolated, because they help in the labors and have children," explains a nun who, in the capital of West African State Burkina Faso, occupies a special residence of more than 100 women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual "social measure".
He issued an informative brochure that should help prevent witch-hunting.
However, this has a catch.
"More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso do not know how to read," notes Die Standard on the disadvantages of writing awareness.
Allegations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Gana, Burkina Faso's neighboring country, 72-year-old Ammy Hemmah died last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to an unfortunate accumulation of circumstances.
According to her version, the woman got caught in the oil used for ritual anointing.
It caught on fire when the group wanted to "expel the evil spirits" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people at all levels of education.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso: "The devourers of human souls always represented a danger," he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to appease witch-hunting, in the Gambia last year the president still participated in it.
"Gambian President Jammeh, after his aunt's death, launched a large hunt for witches who allegedly had been linked to his death and had attempted to kill the president himself by black magic."
"To help him he brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president's personal escort, were forcibly taken from Gambian villages randomly chosen men and women to the president's property in Kanilai," Amnesty International said in its report.
On the farm, the people arrested had to drink a pot of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that also caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of those arrested did not survive their stay on the estate.
After international pressure, about a thousand people were finally released from detention.
Bakala's Tenant: Heats up with coal stoves and signs a higher rent
The man, old and tough, crossed the doors of the customer service center of the company RPG Byty of the "coal magnate" Zdeňek Bakala, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he was carrying some documents with the new three-story leases: his own, his daughter's and his son's, who is serving sentence.
All three have just been caught in rent liberalization.
Instead of 3,500 Czech kroner per month, the child will pay from next year 4,100 kroner for a two-room apartment with separate second-class kitchen.
"In addition, there is no hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," the man shows with his finger in his son's new contract, over whose signature he has full powers.
"But I signed it," explains half angry, half resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as "incorrect and indecent", recommends that tenants not sign the new contracts and wait until December 7, when they will publish a guide informing about how to proceed in these cases.
But in the face of this, man only makes a gesture.
"Everyone says one thing," he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a great test laboratory for liberalisation.
After New Year it will happen with the vast majority of the apartments that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated rent.
That is why Aktualně.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG mining waiting room is one of the four in Ostrava and, on Tuesday at nine, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to them is a number machine.
"Rent 2011", can be read on a bright button of your touch screen.
When you press it, a small piece of paper comes out of the machine with a number.
Almost doesn't give time to read "157" and already the number appears on the big screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in line.
Soon after, an elderly marriage arrives to ask, but the crowd in the room is not here for the new rents.
Most people come to solve common problems, such as in the past: requests for arrangements, insurance issues and similar matters.
Letters with the new rental contracts will arrive in Ostrava to the mailboxes of the tenants of most of the 44,000 apartments belonging to RPG around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes in the letters an increase of the rent of between 15 and 38%.
On November 18, a special window opens at the customer service centre for new rentals.
"It's been working for a week, so it's starting," the workers who find themselves in it when the client presents themselves as a journalist respond briefly.
Liberalization and former mining floors in Bakala are the most sensitive issues in the area.
Before the elections, they were treated loudly and clearly by the Vice-President of Parliament, originally from Ostrava, Lubomír Zaorálek, of the ČSSD, and now they appear continuously in the newspapers of the area.
"Twenty years later I want a new floor."
"They didn't even change my damn bath plate," the man mentioned in the introduction vents.
According to the workers, for the time being they come mostly retired to check if they receive a discount on rent if they sign on time, as promised by the special offer of RPG.
Half of the February rent discount will also be paid to the remaining tenants who sign the new contract before December 15.
However, the window of mining "liberalization" certainly fails to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
"Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, they only asked about the rent in 2011 about forty or fifty people," estimates the window employee.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and on its boards to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the two parties do not reach an agreement on the rent, the matter must be settled by an independent judge.
"It's not a threat, it's information about the only way to proceed possible and completely in accordance with the law," warns RPG on its pages.
"No one is going to be judged here," says one of RPG Byty's employees and a man on the street in front of the customer service center gives him, at least in part, the reason.
"I receive a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left for food; I have no means to go to court," he says.
But, immediately, the employee sows doubt.
"We'll see."
"Mr.Zaorálek warns them in the media not to sign, so people may wait," he says.
Rent regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic at the beginning of 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
"The current rents still do not cover even the amounts necessary for the maintenance of the community fund," recalls Pavel Klimeš, director of the residential portfolio of RPG Byty, who adds that the careless state of the community fund that angers tenants is, for the landlords, the main reason for increasing the rent.
While during the five years between 2005 and 2010, RPG was able to invest in apartments for four billion, in the four years that will go from 2011 to 2014, the figure will increase to 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling, in front of the seats in the waiting room, now repeats some data that stand out in red.
"The increase in rent in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of RPG properties."
"In addition, it will always be a maximum of 7.50 CZK per square metre per month," is indicated on the screen.
Only increase by 38% the rental of 400 floors of RPG's portfolio.
"In such cases, this is an increase from extremely low amounts of 19,66 kroner per square metre," says RPG.
On 2,600 floors, the rental will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that liberalisation will not suddenly affect rents, but will scale from four to eight years.
In addition, it adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the rent rise (see chart) back on the floors, mainly in heating savings: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to people who sign the rent-up agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need day care.
The administrative building Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say that it also hides a small nursery with all the same to such facilities: colored walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outside terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design's employees can come to her.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, from whose study many well-known buildings of Brno emerged, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-guard.
About 90 people work in the company, mainly in the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow the architects and delineators to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, day care is one of the benefits that Arch.Design offers to its workers within the framework of its social program.
The builders and architects thus have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with the care of the children.
The mini-guard was an idea of Arch.Designu's own employees and, with the support of the management, managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-guard is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme for Human Resources and Employment, as well as the State budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding granted (an amount of more than CZK 2.8 million), they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, to recruit qualified staff and services.
When funding runs out (two years), the company Arch.Design has an obligation to keep the mini-guards running with its own funds for three years.
Project preparation lasted one year and Economy Rating contributed to the submission of the funding request.
The care of children is provided by qualified personnel; moreover, a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present for their care throughout the day; the day-care centre currently accommodates children without age limits, although most of them are under the age of three.
Since it is a "mini-garden" it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of the day-care centre is flexible in order to adapt to the needs of the parents and the children of all workers have the same right to use the day-care centre, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although this is an individual education and care, the contents of the mini-care programme are comparable to the regular pre-school curriculum.
Not only do children play, but they also receive quality teaching: from basic learning to school readiness, they teach to English.
The class has not only toys and board games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up children from school late when they are away from their workplace.
Thus, parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally creates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the companies that sign that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program strengthened the marketing of personnel.
The house of bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Look at Gaudí’s interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs resemble the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its skeleton-like shape, the locals nicknamed it "the house of the bones".
Its organic forms, its striking colors, the novel use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of the scales and the omnipresent lines gently curved, all of which is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The front page of the house plays with dream lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, we observe a certain geometry, rhythm and carefully thought out order.
At night, the entire façade of the house seems even more impressive, as it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors improves.
Serpentea and the torsion of the forms continues to surprise us also inside.
The corrugated wood copies the frames of the windows, the railings, the ornaments of the doors, the peepholes and the signs.
The Casa Batlló, located in the Eixample district at number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Grácia, arose from the remodeling of a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of carrying out a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, Casa Batlló, made up of several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in his plans of the project emerged ornaments for the apartment representative of the owner of the property and mosaics used in the facade.
On the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Casa Milá and Gaudí's park Güell, where other pieces of it are found.
Due to its organic shape, the premises shortly after its completion were nicknamed "the house of the bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows began to call it "the house of yawns".
It is also said that, on top of the construction, the sword of Saint George, patron saint of Catalonia, appears.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious motifs.
Gaudí designed in the house a unique system for the central heating season with vents and typical fireplaces.
His forty - five - degree inclination may be strange.
During the construction, Gaudí did not respect the construction rules of the moment at all and did not let himself be influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although evidently in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the city council was so impacted with the result that it asked to be corrected.
He was disturbed, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, on the contrary: only fifteen days after the request of the city council, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The six-story house is completely crossed by a staircase leading to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the halls and a larger group can communicate in this way without problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with Gaudí's reconstruction, not only obtained a new façade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles covering the inner courtyard and skylights.
The game with both colors brings maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was based simply on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb sunlight.
Anyone can visit Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and recharged apartment of those accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that this is a very beneficial business and extended the visits to the common area and the attic, including the roof terrace.
The price of entry to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and tourist card holders get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of the entrance of other Gaudí buildings into the city.
