The army has enough fuses to surround the whole of the Czech Republic, but it only lasts two years.
The Czech army bought 445 kilometers of fuse to burn explosives.
Already last year the Ministry of Defense added 224 kilometers of fuse to its arsenal.
Therefore, they have stocks for 225 years.
The problem is that the life span of the fuse is two years, four at most.
The army bought the explosive fuse from the STV Group, a. s. for 40 million kroner.
The General's staff responded to MF DNES by justifying the purchase of such a huge amount of fuse by saying that the soldiers needed for the training maneuvers 60 kilometers of fuse a year.
According to the calculations of the pyrotechnics of the army, with whom MF DNES was contacted, it is decided, however, that in such a case, they should carry out such maneuvers with frequent use of explosives every year also all generals, high command officers, and even secretaries and cleaners.
Neither Defense Minister Alexandr Vondr nor Army Captain Vlastimil Picek wanted to be exempt.
Only in this way could it be justified for the army to spend 60 kilometres of wick.
This length is equivalent to 25,000 explosions.
Even if it were, the army would have enough stocks for more than ten years.
If on the contrary, as the experts say, for the initial training of each new professional arrives with a maximum of two meters of fuse, the army would have with the new purchase (including adding the consumption of the units of engineers or special) sufficient stocks for the 225 indicated above.
The soldiers of the rapid intervention brigade complained personally to Minister Vondra recently because they say they have little ammunition for various weapons, so they even limit firing practices for money.
And let's not talk about the lack of underwear.
"I also fail to understand that we are repeatedly bought such quantities of wick."
"But it's their decision, and they'll certainly know why they're acting like that."
"For us, the army is a good customer that, as a company, we try to satisfy," admits the commercial director of STV Group, Jan Děcký.
The spokesman for the Ministry of Defence Jan Pejšek defends the hundreds of kilometers of wick also saying that he will have stocks of this "munition" for at least ten years.
However, Jan Děcký of the STV Group indicates that the fuse has a service life of only four years and, in the case of pyrotechnic products for the army or police, two years.
"If stored in perfect conditions, it can last up to four," says one of the soldiers who, due to possible criticism from the army, does not want to give his name.
After the end of its service life, each munition must be carefully checked to see if it remains reliable and will not harm the soldiers.
But these tests are not free and require an additional investment.
Another argument of the Ministry is that, by buying 445 kilometers of wick, he got a discount.
"They cost us 60% less than last year's 244-kilometer order," says spokesman Pejšek of the Ministry of Defence's shopping center.
Just to compare: the annual consumption of wick by the pyrotechnics of the police, which eliminate the ammunition of the Second World War or that left by the Soviet army, no longer exceeds 1,500 meters for years.
In addition, the police always ask only for the right amount to exhaust the ammunition before the end of its useful life.
This was decided for safety reasons for pyrotechnics and, in the meantime, more modern and reliable wick types can be obtained.
The Ministry already has clear difficulties in finishing tens of thousands of tons of ammunition from the time of the Warsaw Pact, when the Czechoslovak army of two hundred thousand people was preparing for a campaign on the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnics with whom MF DNES spoke, after a couple of years there will be the following problem with the current one: we will have to eliminate hundreds of kilometers of old fuse, which is now being bought "barata".
