A Survey that Reveals Ridiculous Rules
The Absurdity survey of the year is part of the business tournament for the fourth time.
He has already managed to eliminate some ridiculous rules.
The unknown winner of the new edition of the Absurdity survey of the year was the obligation to bring to the administration documents that staff members can access online.
The decision was made by more than one third of the nearly 4,000 voters.
For example, the social security administration requested an extract from the business register, although its officials can obtain it with two mouse movements.
Thanks to the survey, this has changed.
"The Czech social security administration will no longer ask for an extract from the business register when it carries out a check on the insured's impositions," said ČSSZ spokesman Jana Buraňová.
The aim of the Absurdity survey of the year is to consult the rules and regulations to be respected by companies and entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic and to try to eliminate those that are absurd.
This year he is a fourth time part of the business tournament of the publication Hospodřské noviny and begins to create hobbies among the general public as well.
While last year's edition had the participation of 3,000 voters, this year it almost reached 4,000.
And it is not surprising, since we still have a number of extra legal obligations that must be respected simply in order to trade.
"Perhaps in the number of papers needed for tax returns we are in the first place worldwide," says Karel Havlíček of the Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic.
Simplification of business rules has been a stated goal of all governments for years.
However, compared to the rest of the world, the situation of improvement especially in the Czech Republic.
According to the World Bank, from the point of view of the conditions for holding a company, the Czech Republic ranks 74th, eight positions worse than last year.
The Absurdity of the Year competition was held for the first time in 2006 and is repeated in the same way each year.
Anyone can indicate any administrative or bureaucratic absurdity every year between April and the end of September, when the contest is closed.
The proposals can be made on the website www.firmaroku.cz. Afterwards, the contest organizer chooses seven candidates for the "anti-prize" and, during October, allows the public to vote on the Internet through www.firmaroku.cz/absurdita and www.ihned.cz.
Win the absurdity that receives the most votes.
For this year's survey, more than one hundred were presented, in particular 105 rules and regulations that make no sense.
The examples were sent by both entrepreneurs and professional associations and journalists.
Among the "finalists" of the competition was, for example, the requirement that vehicles for the maintenance of roads and highways pay the toll or that entrepreneurs with twenty employees, two offices and two bathrooms paint the walls every two years.
The list of seventy proposals this year is published on the pages of the competition.
The announcement of the competition, which always takes place at the beginning of November in Wenceslas Square in Prague, is part of an event in which personalities from the political and social world usually participate.
This year, for example, Eva Svobodová, director of the Association of Small and Medium Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic, or Petr Kužel, president of the Chamber of Commerce of the Republic, attended this event.
"Economic prosperity cannot be sustained if the state continually hinders entrepreneurs, so my goal is to eliminate every year a minimum of thirty paragraphs that currently unnecessarily complicate trade," said Minister of Industry and Trade Martin Kocourek.
Efforts to eliminate absurd regulations are not left in drunken water.
In 2007, what was most disturbing to people was the employer's obligation to communicate three days in advance to the business office of the permanent operating area, the intention to go with a post to a fair or exhibition.
This obligation was removed in the new industrial law.
The obligation that ended second in the number of votes in 2007, that is, the communication to the labour office by its foreign workers of working trips of up to 30 days, was eliminated in the law of the so-called green card.
And the third one goes the charm.
The Absurdity of 2009 was the regulation for physiotherapists to have in their office a large mirror, a refrigerator and two floor scales.
Therefore, this year the Ministry of Health issued a communication saying that it had eliminated the obligation to have a refrigerator.
