The young Czechs get drunk with Fernet and rum. Beer is no longer so, because it works slowly
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from their parents.
These are the drinks that cause young drinkers to end up in medical care at less than fifteen years of age.
Children who end up lying in the hospital continuously to overcome the hangover are no longer an exception.
This is derived from the experience of doctors who encounter such cases in hospital pediatric admissions.
"Drinking beer or wine is no longer fashionable, because it takes a long time to get them drunk."
"Now fashion is strong alcoholic beverages," says the head of pediatrics at Hořovice Hospital in central Bohemia, Luděk Pelikán, to Právo.
"When they get a bottle from their father from the cupboard, it may be whiskey, but it's usually Fernet and vodka."
"Vodka has the advantage that it is lightened with juice and that it does not smell so much," he explains.
This is also confirmed by the spokesperson for the Motol University Hospital, Eva Jurinová.
"Normally, it's usually Fernet or rum."
"These are modern alcoholic beverages, particularly among schoolchildren."
"In some cases, they use spirit they caught at home," adds Jurinová.
According to Chief Pelikán, 13- and 14-year-old drinkers usually appear in hospitals.
Before Hořovice, where he has been working since this year, he worked for a decade in pediatrics in Motol, where ambulances took young people from nearby areas.
"A girl had to enter maybe four times."
"It started when she was twelve, when she was brought in with 3.5 alcohol in her blood, as well as a mixture of ecstasy," says the department's doctor on this case.
"He was at the Holešovice fair at some dance party."
"The interesting thing is that his mother was not surprised that his daughter disappeared 48 hours," the boss is surprised.
It is precisely the parents' lack of interest or even their clear tolerance for drinking by their children that is considered the main cause of the increase in alcohol consumption among young people.
Experts point out that, in the case of children, dependency cannot be spoken of as such.
"Alcoholism means a person who has been chronically dependent on alcohol for several years, with all the phenomena associated with it, which does not occur in children."
"In those who drink alcohol repeatedly, it is rather due to a systematically failed social or family environment," explains Chief Pelikán.
According to spokesman Jurinová, forty drunk children were hospitalized this year at the paediatric clinic in Motol until mid-November.
However, the statistics show only those who come with severe poisoning and must remain in the hospital.
Young drinkers who, after the mobile medical examination, go home to parents or the police, do not count.
In addition to cases where children simply gather after school and drink spirit, there are three seasonal ups and downs for Pelikán: witch day, New Year's Eve and the end of the school year.
"In such a circumstance, they drink for the bad grades or, on the contrary, celebrate the beginning of the vacation."
"On witch day I have come to see in admissions up to seven drunk children at once," Pelikán adds.
Drinkers who spend the night in detoxification under the supervision of doctors, paradoxically, have the advantage that the next day they do not suffer a terrible hangover at home.
Morning headache, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, is avoided with the injection of a serum with glucose and with the nutrients that the body lacks.
"These are doing much better, because after the agitated night, they get up well and don't hurt at all."
"They are only confused about where they are," Pelikán says, adding that patients often lose their good mood at least when they see the costs they have generated.
The ambulance transfer and hospitalization in a serious patient room cost about ten thousand crowns.
"I have often used the cost as a means of educating them, when during the visit I tell the children directly how much their drunkenness has cost and that they would have to spend all summer in a job for young people to earn enough to pay for that night," adds Pelikán.
Health insurance, in his view, perhaps as a retrogressive measure, which usually pays people back the costs of treatment, does not do so in the case of drinking children.
