But problems can still arise if the electoral authority declares that Mr Célestin, who has little support, if any, has moved on to the second round.
Given that the cholera epidemic was raging the country and more than a million earthquake survivors continued to live in tents, a large abstention was expected.
At the time, many Haitians wanted to vote, but failed to do so due to a lack of organization.
About 250,000 identity documents, needed to vote, had not yet been distributed shortly before the elections.
There's a lot at stake.
Aid donors see the election of a legitimate and popular government as an essential step in the reconstruction of Haiti.
And, as it has become clear, so do the Haitians themselves.
Pushing tiptoe towards the center
In the weeks since she lost her husband, Cristina Fernández, the president of Argentina, she has enjoyed great sympathy among the public that has increased her popularity rate by 20 points, to more than 50%, the highest level she has recorded since her election in 2007.
In spite of everything, that can turn it into a successful campaign for a second term in next year's elections will depend on whether the clearly affected Mrs. Fernández leaves aside the intransigence of her late husband, her predecessor and political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And, at this point, the indications are inconclusive.
Mr Kirchner, who continued to take charge of economic policy even after his wife succeeded him as president, had the habit of drawing up budgets that undervalued tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the presidential marriage to spend the extra income at its discretion.
In theory, Mrs. Fernández's government lost its majority in Congress last year.
However, the opposition is divided, a situation that has worsened following Kirchner's death as a result of a heart attack on 27 October.
Some dissenting members of the Peronist movement in power have faced Mrs. Fernández.
However, after some chaotic sessions in which one deputy punched another in the face and other deputies accused the government of bribery, Congress decided to reject the 2011 budget.
"I'm not going to argue," the president said.
The 2010 budget will therefore be implemented next year, which will give the president an even greater margin of action when spending it.
The economy is improving considerably: it is likely to grow to 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently at 11.1 per cent, but many private estimates, in addition to the wage demands of trade unions, place it at about 30 per cent.
Mr Kirchner, who took power in 2003 when Argentina was on the verge of economic collapse, made growth and poverty reduction his priorities, rather than controlling inflation.
He refused to negotiate with the IMF, pressured the private sector and made INDEC, the statistical institute, adapt official inflation statistics.
Will President Fernández now moderate these policies?
It has convened meetings between the private sector and union leaders.
In addition, its staff members claim that they want to limit salary increases next year to 18 per cent.
The economy has been driven by the high prices of Argentine agricultural exports worldwide.
However, inflation has limited the momentum to growth achieved with a large devaluation in 2002.
Perhaps for this reason Mrs Fernández is showing signs of wanting to restore Argentina's financial ties with the rest of the world.
At the beginning of the year, the government reached an agreement with bondholders who had refused a forced pre-restructuring of the debt that Argentina had not paid in 2001.
At present, it seems that Mrs Fernández is about to conclude an agreement with the creditor governments grouped in the Paris Club, to which she owes about $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners always insisted that this would not involve IMF supervision, as usual.
However, last month Amado Boudou, the Minister of Economy, announced that the Fund will offer "technical assistance" to develop a new national consumer price index, which seems to be the prelude to cleaning up the INDEC.
It is not clear whether President Fernández wants to remain in politics when she finishes her term of office, given that she no longer has her husband at her side.
If he does, he will need to win the support of the middle class, much of which has been tired of Kirchnerism.
When the Argentines return from their summer vacation in March, the wave of sympathy for her will have declined.
If you want to win other elections, you will have to decide whether or not to repudiate, calmly, many of your husband's policies.
Half hurrah for China
Voters in Taiwan are slowly approaching a kind of closer union with the continent.
What does Taiwan think about its big brother across the strait?
More than 7.5 million voters, 70% of those eligible, came on November 27 to elect mayors and councillors from five urban districts in what seems to be a comprehensive assessment of the president, Ma Ying-jeou.
Mr Ma himself has become a defender of sentiments for the continent, forging innovative business ties, including a partial free trade pact, the biggest change in relations with China since 1949.
Mr. Ma passed the test, but almost.
Although his Kuomintang party (KMT) won three of the five municipal elections, he failed to obtain a majority of the votes.
Instead, the progressive democratic Party (PPD), which has opted for full independence from Taiwan, won almost 50% of all votes against 45% of the KMT.
If it were the presidential ones, Mr Ma would be in trouble.
Since his election two years ago, his party's voting share has fallen by about 8%.
For the first time, the PDP tied up with the KMT in the city halls.
In the elections you could see the typical elements of the Taiwanese elections, including noisy campaign trucks and large crowds with banners and light girls dancing clothes.
There was also the mysterious attempt at rigorous murder.
Sean Lien, the son of Lien Chan, honorary president of the KMT, was campaigning for one of the KMT candidates the night before the election.
A man in the crowd shot the young man directly in the face, wounding him and killing a passer-by.
The funny thing is that it has not been possible to determine whether the man intended to harm Lien or to avenge the candidate.
In any case, says Tsai Ing-wen, the PDP leader, the shooting affected the elections, sowing suspicions about the PDP and causing voters to lean towards the KMT.
Maybe the only big winner of the campaign was China.
It was surprising that the issue of the continent itself was not addressed.
Instead, the candidates spoke of public accommodation and job creation plans.
Taiwan normally enjoys its de facto independence and detests the military threat from China.
Therefore, the KMT tends to avoid publicizing its links with the government in Beijing.
But this time the PDP also avoided encouraging sentiment against China.
It responds to the new awareness that Chinese trade is essential for Taiwan's economic survival.
For his part, Mr Ma stated that it had been confirmed that his policy towards China was acceptable to the majority of Taiwanese.
The Beijing Government is expected to continue to bribe them with trade, in line with its strategy to return Taiwan to the fold.
China did not waste time sending a negotiator to Taipei to prepare for a summit on investment protection and medical cooperation.
He would certainly also like to achieve political integration, but first things first.
It will be best to wait for the 2012 presidential elections to pass.
In any case, the PDP has been reinvented.
Two years ago he was in a bad situation: his former leader, Chen Shui-bian, was imprisoned on charges of corruption.
Between 2000 and 2008, he openly instigated explicit independence.
However, under the leadership of Mrs.Tsai, a new generation of moderates has emerged and the PDP is striving to attract professionals and young people.
Mrs Tsai has been welcomed as a PDP candidate for the presidency, as has Her Tseng-chang, who served under Chen.
His party is now doing its utmost to demonstrate that it can also have relations with Beijing.
Ms Tsai announced plans to set up an expert group to act as a point of contact between the PDP and China, provided that negotiations can be conducted without preconditions.
Mrs Tsai tells the Taiwanese public that her party represents a "reliable alternative" to Mr Ma's hasty approach to China.
Mr. Chen seems furious about the change.
In a statement issued from his cell, he stated that the PDP candidates would have been better off if they had insisted that Taiwan was an independent country.
He even ordered Mr. Su, a pragmatic, not to run for president.
Even without Mr. Chen's intervention, the PDP will have difficulty choosing from among its potential candidates.
The KMT must also conduct an examination of conscience.
Mr Ma's assessments have been poor, despite impressive economic growth; the KMT candidates have not wanted to campaign with him.
Their lack of popularity seems to be mainly due to unemployment and the growing gap between rich and poor.
A KMT spokesman says he will restructure his cabinet as well as local teams.
Large PDP samples suggest Taiwan's support for a rapprochement is limited.
At the same time, most Taiwanese consider economic integration with China inevitable.
According to Antonio Chiang, a well-known columnist, "the point of no return has already been crossed."
