The lion is ready to roar again, while the restructuring of MGM gets final court approval
After 18 months of confusion and uncertainty, MGM has finally achieved green light to start over.
On Thursday, a federal bankruptcy judge in New York officially approved the creditors' "pre-armed" plan to clear approximately $5 billion of debt, paving the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company to focus its efforts on producing and releasing movies and TV programs.
Thursday's ruling confirms that the plan meets the requirements of the U.S. bankruptcy code, so there are no other legal obstacles to MGM's reliving under the founders of Spyglass Entertainment, Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become the chief executives of what will be a small study.
Staff will be reduced from 400 to approximately 320.
In reality, MGM will not leave Chapter 11 until JPMorgan Chase closes a $500 million planned credit instrument to finance the operations and productions of the new MGM.
The investment bank is currently syndicating the credit, which on its own is contributing $75 million, and is expected to be funded by mid-December.
The restructuring process of the study began in May 2009, when the Moelis and Co. investment bank was hired to give advice on the management necessary to manage its finances, while struggling to make interest payments for $300 million a year.
In August, Director Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former President of Enron and expert in recovery of bankrupt companies, known for his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis and Cooper's attempts to resolve MGM's financial tribulations and satisfy the study's more than 140 creditors took much longer than expected.
After several months of discussions, at the end of 2009 the parties agreed to put the company on sale.
However, the auction attracted few bidders and none willing to pay the more than $2 billion sought by creditors.
Before the spring of this year, he returned to the design table as the MGM team began working on a restructuring plan that, after months of internal debate and disagreements, was finally backed by creditors at the end of October.
When MGM officially comes out of bankruptcy in the coming weeks, Moelis and Cooper companies will receive multimillion dollar bonuses for their work.
Moelis and Co., who has already received $1.2 million, will get a $9.5 million payment.
Cooper's companies, which have been raising $375,000 a month for their company management services, will receive $4 million in "success fees."
Barber and Birnbaum plan to resume production at MGM, which premiered only one film this year, and collected an annual board of seven or eight films that will be released in 2012.
They also plan to co-finance two films based on "The Hobbit", along with Warner Bros.
The studio needs to arrange a separate loan of $265 to $275 million to finance its share of those two films, which will be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who owns approximately 18% of MGM's debt, had been trying to arrange a merger of the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, in which he is the largest shareholder.
However, recent discussions between the two companies did not result in an agreement.
Tech Toys wants to keep the balance of its gift budget
While the iPad is the main candidate to be the most wonderful toy this year, followed perhaps by the Microsoft Kinect video game system, both can mean a significant dent in your gift budget.
