A more moderate side of law and order maintenance in China is promoted
As an urban instructor sergeant, Tang Shenbin marked the passage in a city square, severely inspecting the nervous persons in his charge, issuing orders quietly with military authority.
He wanted the female members of Chengguan, China’s corpulent urban order police, feared and despised by their capricious energetic measures and their inclination to violence, to convey a certain impression to a handful of spectators.
"Shut up!"
"Attention!"
Show them, he whispered, "How are the pretty girls!"
Four girls who barely spent their teens wearing white gloves and identical olive green jackets and tight pants to attract attention.
Four pairs of black shoes perfectly aligned.
Four elegant hats perfectly placed on top of the hair tied with bows with blue and white stripes.
"Personally, I think they look normal," said Mr Tang, scornfully.
"The models are cute."
More than one government has tried to clean up the image of China’s urban inspectors.
One city ordered all new recruits to have a degree.
Guangdong Province changed the greyish green color from uniforms to a supposedly more attractive blue.
Wuhan, in central China, replaced the use of force with intimidating glances: in 2009, according to a report, 50 officers surrounded a dismal snack cart, and watched it frown constantly for half an hour, until the street vendor picked up his stuff and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 inhabitants in Chengdu, has chosen a radical makeover.
Since 2003, the district has added 13 women to its urban police force, specifically elected for their appearance, proportion and youth.
The idea is to give the rough cop a softer, more feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson would have to fight to increase China's scant respect for these city squadrons.
And for good reason, critics would argue.
Unlike the police, these officers are authorized only to enforce city ordinances, imposing fines and other administrative penalties.
But Chinese news media routinely portray a different reality.
In January 2008, inspectors from Hubei Province beat a passerby to death after using their cell phone to film them while dissolving a protest against a waste dump.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing inspectors was stolen and published on the Internet, describing how to effectively whip criminals without causing them to bleed.
This year, a traveling watermelon salesman from Shanghai suffered brain damage after a brawl with five officers.
A video game full of violence, available for download online, presents Chinese-trained inspectors who attack street vendors.
"Chengguan has left a scar in the government," lamented China Daily, a national publication, last year after another controversy over tactics.
The newspaper demanded "a really meticulous cleaning."
Skeptics say that the current approach is far from this.
After the district requested eight new female recruits through a notice in October, an editorial on The Beijing Evening News wondered if women had real duties or were simply a stage distraction.
The answer seems to be a little bit of both.
The district's announcement called for female candidates aged 18 to 22, with a good figure "and the five harmonious facial features."
They should have a height above average, greater than 1.6 meters or 5 feet, 2 1⁄2 inches.
Withdrawal at the age of 26 is compulsory.
Officials said the work was physically too hard for women over 25.
"His image is the important thing," an anonymous district official told Rednet.com, a quasi-government website.
"First, the external qualities of the candidates will determine whether they meet the requirements, such as height, weight, facial features, etc."
Then comes the temperament "and the inner qualities".
The female Chengguan are like vases, he said, and added, "Besides being vases, they will have other responsibilities."
Zheng Lihua, deputy director of the district city administration office, is not eager to support that description.
