Can civics build a bridge to unite divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invectiveness and negativity, a bit of civicism has been unleashed in Washington this week.
Is it a harbinger of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan combat in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and Congressional leaders did not bring about any progress on the major issues that should be addressed during the outgoing session.
But from what they all say, it was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two sides, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than being another empty episode to gain partisan points.
The Wednesday public meeting of the president's deficit committee was also civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates members.
That is barely enough to state that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Both sides are now in a trial period, testing each other to identify signs of cooperativeism and commitment, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
The reason why the Tuesday meeting and subsequent evaluations of the meeting by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and deeply rooted to suggest any rapid change in the climate that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it is taxes, expenditure, health care or social assistance, the two sides are at opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed with regard to the way things are said," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
"They are inevitable after the elections.
The elections arouse party passions, which then become extinct.
That's good."
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing session, the Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts are due at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of this.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment benefits, probably because Republicans cannot make believe they are in favour of tax cuts for the rich, denying unemployment benefits for unemployed workers.
Following Tuesday's meeting in the White House, there is greater optimism about possible treatment of these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty) nuclear disarmament pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continuous bipartisanship when the new 112th Congress meets in January.
He stated, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement will begin.
"After the things to be done are done, in the short term psychology will reverse the situation to one of confrontation," he said.
Wehner also expressed scepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civics can lead to genuine cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as an essay for the main event of 2012," he said.
The motives have a lot to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters of the Tea Party, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As much as Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know they must try to keep their promises to cut state spending and overturn the new health law.
These support lines are already evident in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit commission, which include the reform of the tax code and the increase in some taxes and retirement age, and the cutback in expenditure.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken care of one of the most difficult work in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have forcibly introduced the issue of the deficit in the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member commission to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the officials elected to the panel, suggesting that there is at least currently little basis or desire for compromise in fiscal matters.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the Republicans of the White House and those of Congress.
The first will happen next year in the form of partisan clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama about the budget, taxes, and medical care, followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would bring about change?
Public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If confrontation leads to a stalemate, as happened in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the people.
Whoever they think is losing will probably change course and seek compromise.
However, this may be an optimistic view.
Partidism and polarization are now larger than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a bigger ideological gap between Obama and Republicans in Congress than there was between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more transcendental election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilism shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
