Without detracting from the ability as a driver of the final champion, the German Sebastian Vettel, nor from the ability of the Renault engine that propels his car, in the world of Formula 1 has become a legend the "secret weapon" that the multinational Siemens has put in the hands of Red Bull to make it a winning team.
This is actually a powerful process simulation software that the German company put on the market in 2007 for purposes far removed from the high car competition.
Named PLM, this powerful computer tool has been used to design assembly chains for manufacturing factories around the world, power plants, high-precision instruments.
The objective is to reproduce, faithfully simulate the product or process before building it in a real way, thus avoiding faults and avoidable expenses.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon's cameras, Sukhoi's aircraft or Nissan's most famous utility cars.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens' industrial division, explains that the use of this computer instrument in its Formula 1 factory has allowed Red Bull to design and implement "in a few hours, almost in real time", the modifications, changes and improvements that are detected during races and in trials.
Russwurm explains that the teams in 1992 had an average of 10 technicians on their team who were able to make a maximum of three or four vehicle improvements during each season.
The Red Bull team today employs 180 young high-skilled professionals who, equipped with powerful computer equipment, analyze and project all kinds of modifications to the tanks.
Siemens manager explained that the PLM software is capable of analyzing and improving all elements of the Red Bull boosters with the exception of the engine, which is the entire responsibility of Renault.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety elements are modified.
The changes can be brought from the virtual reality of the simulator to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced laser production systems and high-tech autoclaves.
The only limitation of this technological improvement madness is the figure of $40 million that each Formula 1 team can spend at most in each season to facilitate competition.
Red Bull has set up the high-tech factory to design and produce its fires in a locality about 50 kilometers from London.
These are two buildings where visits are restricted, especially for journalists.
Everything that happens there is considered "high secret."
The staff for this task amounts to 580 people, including their two drivers, champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
Red Bull's Formula One hero is undoubtedly the recent champion Sebastian Vetell.
