Go ahead that Merkel's position is not a mistake in his communicative policy.
On the contrary, it is another twist in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And there Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with that of maintaining the old traditions of a large part of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate about the three possible solutions to the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, made up of herself, Austria and Holland, among other countries, while the south would leave the monetary area.
The second is the recovery of the framework, although it now seems like science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, close to 50% of the population.
The third is a redesign of the euro, in line with the German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigour, fines for transgressing countries, possible suspensions of payments from one of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defined for a long time, so now there are no excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission stimulated deficits, the German government pulled a constitutional reform out of hand to prevent them from beginning in 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany believed should be done (plans of fiscal rigour and stability in public finances), and what its European partners, including France, were practicing.
The second on the front was given by the Central European country when Merkel painfully extended Greece's rescue decision.
He was already the object of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public opinion and the published one were very much against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, once again Merkel emerges with a clear position, demanding the reform of the Union's treaties, in order to make possible the rescue of a country and, at the same time, to force private lenders to bear part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has precipitated the Irish crisis and everything else.
But his proposal, although somewhat sweetened, has been approved and, in the coming months, we should attend the process of reform of the Union that will enable those measures from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And he is telling us all that, although we must now take measures with which he may not agree very much, from that date the old operation of the euro will be over.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary area, in which the offending countries will be severely punished, they can be forced to declare themselves suspended and, in this case, the private sector will also bear part of the cost.
Germany is pointing out to us that we must follow a severe path of growth with high savings and investment rates, consumption moderation, productivity and competitiveness improvements and positive external balances.
Another alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, such as the one that has presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, will simply not tolerate it.
The delivery is clear.
And we would do wrong not to understand it.
It is not just a question of bringing the government deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What they demand is much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these circumstances is deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will give way to greater tranquillity.
And let's take advantage of the window of opportunity we've been given, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also understood this and his double manifesto (the reforms promised after last Saturday's meeting with the big companies and yesterday's announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite the criticisms of Merkel, the thesis that order must be put at home has been opened.
But the red line that Germany has drawn there is, and it doesn't look like they're going to move it.
And, among the possibilities envisaged, the possibility of leaving a monetary area too crowded with unserious countries cannot be excluded.
Then Germany will always be able to tell us that it had already warned us.
Sport and fraud of law
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos before the Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but will not escape a sanction.
The expulsion allegedly ordered by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League has caused rivers of ink to be written about whether or not such behavior is anti-sportive and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, in the absence of a few minutes to finish the game (which his team already had clearly won), the two players deliberately lost time in taking faults to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid will end up as leader of its group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction the next game of the league, against the Auxerre, and they will be able to pass clean cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee has sanctioned with two matches the team's coach, José Mourinho, and with different financial amounts the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the unwritten rules, but in a row, of this sport.
Part of the debate that arose in the case reported is because it has been led by a team from the entity of Real Madrid (which in its anthem presumes of nobility and honor, and which in past times has fined its players for similar acts) and the orchestrated dramatization, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his long history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behaviour not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions commit fraud by law; for, in fact, they are actions that respect the sports regulations, but seem to circumvent their meaning.
The question is what kind of damage they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the assets that includes the sports spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions was not put in danger, that is, there was no violent play.
Another of these assets that is alluded to with fair play is to prevent the offending players' team from unfairly taking advantage of the opposing team, which also did not happen.
However, the paradox of the action of Real Madrid players is that they did not conform to what we normally characterize as a trap or fraud of law, since their violation of the rules was not made in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but precisely their action tried to be the most obvious in order to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage offenders gain from intentional misdemeanours examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that the rival is not put in a disadvantageous position nor is profit obtained in the same game, since obviously the result of the action involves leaving the team itself with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, as the club won't be able to count on those players.
The advantage, obviously, is that players will begin the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the team can be eliminated at the first of the changes, and also with this performance the players fulfill a penalty game and move to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension due to accumulation of cards occurs with a less than in the first cycle.
So, if you go through rounds, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against the sporting spirit, of which it is part to make strategic decisions that favor making the most of what the rules allow.
In the case before us, the players did not act to evade the application of the sanction (this would be a clear case of law fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without circumventing the punishment or running away from it.
Although the border between ingenuity and law fraud is diffuse, on this occasion I believe it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises from two factors: because it was two self-expulsions and the way in which the directive was transmitted to provoke them.
The damage caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as it is aesthetic.
