Hydro-Quebec has awarded direct contracts worth $450 million to engineering companies for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert hydroelectric project.
At the heart of this avalanche of more than 100 contracts is a consortium formed by the companies BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor, which has obtained without a tender the most important contract, the one of project management, for a sum of 295 million.
The consortium, called Énergie gérance, was created in 2004 following Hydro-Québec's decision to entrust the private sector with its responsibility to manage this major $5 billion hydroelectric project.
In early 2005, the consortium Énergie gérance obtained the lucrative contract without prior public tender.
For the Quebec Party, the use of consortia of companies poses a serious ethical problem that threatens to eliminate competition and provoke a rise in prices.
"This is a new method of collusion and eliminating competition."
"That is to say, people, instead of doing it secretly, now do it openly," said the Quebec Party deputy Sylvain Simard at a press conference yesterday.
Earlier in the morning, Mr Simard raised the issue in the National Assembly because, he says, he does not understand how the public interest can benefit in this way.
The Minister of Natural Resources, Nathalie Normandeau, responded in the afternoon, strongly denying that there was a collusion with this contract.
"I begin to tire," he protested, arguing that the PQ had acted in a "dishonest" way and "with lack of rigor."
He pointed out that "the minimum" would be for the PQ to apologize.
The consortium formula is a common practice throughout the world.
Normally, it is an alliance with a time limit that allows two or more companies to pool their knowledge to respond to a tender for a complex project.
The Eastmain project presents a high level of complexity, taking into account the magnitude of the works.
The works have already started and will last until 2012.
In all cases, the contract has been awarded without competition being involved; it has been a negotiation.
In addition, the consortium formula has ceased to be the exception to the standard in Quebec, even for relatively simple projects.
As published last week by Le Devoir, the consortium formula in the technical advice sector is being investigated in the Government.
A quick look at Quebec's business register allows identifying more than 200 consortia, some of which seem permanent.
In this way, Dessau works in partnership with most of its main competitors, such as CIMA+, Génivar, SNC-Lavalin, Roche et Tecsult, and others.
Each combination, and there are dozens of them, leads to a single legal person, that is, Dessau.
Regarding the consortium Énergie gérance, Minister Normandeau has emphasized that "the territory of James Bay responds to a particular workforce dynamic and Hydro-Québec responds specifically to it since the 1970s".
The great head of the Eastmain project, Réal Laporte, of the Société d'énergie de la Baie James (SEBJ), has given an explanation that has highlighted the fact that the project management contract has been awarded directly.
"If you respond to a bid and there are few participants, your prices are going to be higher."
"You have two options: you can get in touch with the actors in the sector and tell them: we are going to negotiate a satisfactory agreement with a good price."
"However, the idea is that what matters is not the price, but the competition of people," said Mr Laporte.
The contract awarded to the consortium Énergie gérance is part of a long list of contracts of more than $50,000 obtained by the Quebec Party.
The contracts were awarded by Hydro-Quebec or SEBJ for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert project.
Following the verification, Le Devoir has identified 109 technical advice contracts awarded between 2002 and March 2010 to companies or their subsidiaries, in particular geotechnical laboratories.
SNC-Lavalin has obtained 22 contracts, Génivar obtained 16, Tecsult 14 and Dessau 10, without taking into account its participation in Énergie gérance.
All contracts were negotiated.
In total, they amount to $449,783,344, including the Énergie gérance contract of $295,131,564.
Sylvain Simard has implied that the four companies that form the consortium (BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor) are "well known to the Liberal Party of Quebec".
Minister Normandeau has dropped that the PQ is also linked to these companies, which "finance" it, before specifying that it is rather about its leaders.
