Similarly, only 14.6 per cent of Quebecers take politicians' speeches on this issue seriously.
In any case, information on responsible consumption seems essential to stimulate this sector of consumption, currently supported by about one third of Quebec's consumers.
In fact, the gaps and doubtful nature of the information mean that 46% of consumers discard this option.
This is the second obstacle identified by the Barometer, after the highest price of these products.
In addition, one third of Quebecers say they are also suspicious of the supposed yields of the ecological products or services they are trying to sell to them.
On the other hand, almost half of consumers changed their habits in 2010 and, especially, changed the brand of one or more products to respect their convictions.
61% have given priority to shopping in the shops in their neighborhood and have preferred to buy food products grown in their region, says the Barometer.
More green and responsible (the responsible consumption index has reached 64 points over a maximum of one hundred this year), the Homo consumer of Quebec loves to occupy the post of the king of recycling that tries to reduce its impact on the environment by worrying about the protection of the fauna.
