Avenger hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks issue has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandalous in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at international level and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is confirmation of the fact that each file created by a secret service (regardless of the nation to which it belongs) is made up exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual customs only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Khadafi's sinisterly ridiculous profile has long given cabaret artists ideas to create their sketches.
The rule that secret records should only be made up of news of public knowledge is essential for the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you visit a bookshop dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosacruz) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for novelties about the nonexistent), but because those who dedicate themselves to occultism not only trust what they already know, which reconfirms what they have already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as he is lazy (or has little desire) the head of the secret services (if it could not be, I don't know, editor of the Libération), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi sent by the US Embassy of Rome to the State Department was the same as that published by Newsweek the week before.
So why have the revelations of these files caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, that is, that embassies, at least since World War II and since the Heads of States can call themselves by telephone or catch the plane for dinner, have lost their diplomatic role and, with the exception of some limited representation exercises, have become spy centres.
Any viewer who watches research films knows perfectly well, we just pretend we don't know it out of hypocrisy.
In any case, public repetition violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea of anyone being able to consult the most secret secrets of the world's most powerful country significantly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the "greens".
But let us enter into the true nature of what has happened.
Formerly, in the time of Orwell, he could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy has come true since, being able to control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as is the case now, that even crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the avenger of citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that can no longer keep its own secrets endure?
It is true, as Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without secret, since it comes from the public sphere; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means to take away all power.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and a lot, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put any classified information on the Internet, as it would be like posting it on a billboard in the street.
But it is also clear that, with current technologies, you cannot expect to have confidential conversations over the phone.
Nothing is easier than to find out whether and when a Head of State has flown and contacted one of the counterparts.
How can they maintain private and confidential relations in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my foresight is science fiction and, therefore, novel, but I imagine government agents moving discreetly on errands with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned from memory or, at best, hiding some data written on their shoes' heels.
That information is then kept in a single copy in locked drawers: after all, the Watergate's attempted espionage was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology is currently advancing like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the cordless telegraph has revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a telegraph with cables (telephones).
The video tapes (analogs) had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, moving forward and backward, discovering all the secrets of the editing, while now the CDs (digital) only allow to advance or back from chapter to chapter, that is, to huge proportions.
With the high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the journeys that it entails, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary that politics and communication techniques take us back to horse cars.
One last comment.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was being secretly plotted in embassies.
At present, it is embassies that request confidential information from the press.
Climate: France’s Shatters in their Financing Pledges
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to consider whether the rapidly unblocked pledges of funding (called fast start or early start) made by developed countries have been honoured.
And the French slugs have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries pledged $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union committed to providing EUR 7,2 billion over three years and France EUR 1,260 million (i.e. EUR 420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put on the table its best letters to convince its partners that their commitment to fast start financing is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation was an appreciable result and appreciated for what it really is worth: developing countries and civil society would want all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released 2010 €2.2 billion, placing it on the right track towards fulfilling its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without harming official development assistance.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
At present, each one chooses the reference that suits him best.
For example, the European Commission has taken 2009 as its reference: international funding is maintained and 150 million is added in three years as fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references for the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to expenditure in previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, France's total amount of aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while respecting its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element is the sharing of donations and loans.
Once again, there is no standard and everyone chooses the method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that each euro borrowed is equivalent to a donated euro.
Clearly, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain profitable investments (often emissions reduction projects based on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present a euro that is to be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated... At most, only the cost of the loan to the lending country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be calculated for its commitments.
But France does not find such reasoning useful: "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% grants (36.1 million euros); consult the EU document to see it for your own eyes.
This is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it by 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union provides a euro to fulfil its commitment, France only contributes ten cents and considers the effort comparable.
A good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France is making a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to the actions over time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
Spending only €36.1 million, he manages to give the impression that he spends 420 million "new and additional", as he promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has dealt with arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in the negotiations, since developing countries are not fools...
The chapter on early financing is relatively short-term in relation to the climate negotiations as a whole.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it's not like that.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early financing.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
In particular, however, France could move forward with discussions on the stakes at stake in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the question of the "additional nature" or the method of computing loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on this issue as it is on others.
We therefore have the hope of the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of the "additional character" and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to move the negotiations forward.
Warning on pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old ingests 81 different chemicals on a day, according to a study published on Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (the former movement for rights and respect for future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have a significant statistical value taking into account the limited number of samples analyzed, but they are illustrative of the problem addressed", acquired in supermarkets of Oise and Paris between July and September the foods that a child of about ten years old usually consumes in four meals and a snack a day.
These model meals, which comply with official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruits and vegetables, three of dairy products and 1.5 litres of water per day), as well as sweets, were examined in laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance of the dish is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances susceptible to acting as endocrine disruptors (PE), according to studies by various institutions such as the International Cancer Research Centre.
"Although, in virtually all cases, the legal limits for each chemical are not exceeded individually, our study clearly shows that the exposure of consumers to potentially carcinogenic pollutants and/or PE is worrying," the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three considered as safe carcinogens, as well as about twenty residues that may harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for the school, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide prohibited in France.
The same applies to green beans from Kenya, included in food, in which the study has detected traces of a potent banned insecticide in the EU.
In addition, the Russian steak, canned tuna and even the bread bar or chewing gum were seasoned with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, analyses found the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon slice was the most "nutrient" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic dish used to heat food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The final risk posed by these "pollutant cocktails" to the consumer is "probably underestimated," the study says.
The Europe Ecology-Les Verts Alliance (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "in the face of the gravity of the situation" to apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the increase in diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
